{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-12-20","name":"William de Lovetot Lord of Hallamshire","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"William de Lovetot Lord of Hallamshire","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"William"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"de Lovetot"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Suffix","value":"Lord of Hallamshire"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"1105–1178","fullLifespan":"Abt 1105–1178","portrait":{"url":"https://tree-portraits-pgp.familysearchcdn.org/iccgm/thumb200s.jpg","@type":"ImageObject"},"birthDate":"+1105","deathDate":"+1178","deathPlace":{"address":"Yorkshire, England","geo":{"latitude":53.95878,"longitude":-1.08248,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"William de Lovetot, Lord of Hallamshire, possibly descended from the Norman Baron Ricardus Surdus, was an Anglo-Norman Baron from Huntingdonshire, often credited as the founder of Sheffield, England.\n\nIt is unknown when De Lovetot acquired an interest in the manor of Hallamshire, but by the early twelfth century (in the reign of Henry I) he was in possession of Hallam, Attercliffe, Sheffield, Grimesthorpe, Greasbrough and Worksop. He also had interests in Handsworth, Treeton, and Whiston . He founded a priory at Worksop c.1103, St. Mary's Church at Handsworth, and may have founded the parish church in Sheffield at around this time.\n\nLovetot is credited with the building of a motte and bailey castle in Sheffield. Along with the castle, a hospital was established at what is still called \"Spital Hill\", a mill was built beside the River Don, and a bridge called Lady's Bridge was constructed where there had previously only been a ford across the river. Little is known of Sheffield prior to Lovetot, but these developments established Sheffield as the main town in the Hallamshire area.\n\nWilliam had four sons, with his wife Emma: \nRichard, estimated birth 1101. Calculated birth 1130 Following the death of William de Lovetot the manor of Hallamshire passed to his elder son, Richard de Lovetot, and then to Richard's son, William de Lovetot, before being passed to Gerard de Furnival by his marriage to Maud de Lovetot in about 1204.  Richard de Luvetot had Sheffield and Wirksop.  His Son Richard de Luvetot had Sheffeild and Wirksop, and the Lands on the North Side Trent, in this County.  Ricardus de Lovetot de Wirksop married Cecelia.  Richard de Lovetot, Lord of Hallamshire m. Cecilia\n\nNigel, another of his Sons, had the Barony in Huntingtonshire, ten Knights Fees, and five Knights Fees of the Honor of Roger de Busli, which lay on the South Side Trent, in this County. This Nigellus accounted, for twenty Marks of his Knights in Cambridge or Huntingtonshires, by his Certificate, which he, as other Barons did, at that Time sent in to the King. It appeared that of his whole Barony none were enfeoffed since the Death of King Henry the First. Nigellus de Lovetot married Margar. Nigel or Nigellus of Worksop\n\nHenry, Estimated birth, 1109\n\nHugh, Estimated birth, 1113\n\nFollowing the death of William de Lovetot the manor of Hallamshire passed to his elder son, Richard de Lovetot, and then to Richard's son, William de Lovetot, before being passed to Gerard de Furnival by his marriage to Maud de Lovetot in about 1204.","events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1105","date":"Abt 1105"},{"name":"Marriage","sources":"0","year":"1130","date":"before 1130","place":"England","type":"Spousal","age":"24","id":"G273-149"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1130","date":"Abt 1130","place":"Yorkshire, England","age":"25","id":"GK99-7HW"},{"name":"Death of Spouse","sources":"0","year":"1132","date":"Aft 1132","place":"Nottinghamshire, England","age":"28","id":"G273-149"},{"name":"Death of Child","sources":"0","year":"1161","date":"Aft 1161","age":"57","id":"GK99-7HW"},{"name":"Death","sources":"0","year":"1178","date":"1178","place":"Yorkshire, England","age":"73"}